6. RADIATION HARDENING

6.1 Radiation Effects Modeling

Bit Error Rate Calculation:
For LEO environment:
$BER = BER_0 \cdot e^{-d/\lambda} \cdot \Phi$
where:

· $BER_0$: Surface error rate (10⁻⁵/bit/day)
· $d$: Shielding thickness (5 mm Ta)
· $\lambda$: Attenuation length (5 mm for Ta)
· $\Phi$: Flux enhancement (10× in SAA)

HD Radiation Tolerance:
With $D=1536$, $s=0.08$:

· Random errors: $\text{Accuracy} = e^{-BER \cdot D \cdot s}$
· For $BER = 10^{-4}$: Accuracy = 0.988
· For $BER = 10^{-3}$: Accuracy = 0.885
· For $BER = 10^{-2}$: Accuracy = 0.286

Burst Error Analysis:
Burst size $B$ affects $N_{\text{affected}}$ bits:
$N_{\text{affected}} = B \cdot (1 - e^{-sD/B})$
With interleaving: $N_{\text{affected}} \approx \sqrt{B \cdot sD}$

6.2 Hardening Techniques

1. Interleaving:

· 8-bit granularity spreads adjacent logical bits
· Minimum distance: 24 channels (2 wavelengths × 12 ports)
· Burst resistance improvement: 40-60%

2. Triple Modular Redundancy (TMR):
Critical electronic components:

· Voting logic for state machines
· Triple voting with mismatch detection
· Overhead: 200% area, 50% power

3. Error Detection & Correction:

· Hamming(22,16) code for memory
· 37.5% overhead, corrects 1-bit, detects 2-bit errors
· CRC-32 for data transmission

4. Watchdog Timers:

· Independent hardware timers
· 10 ms timeout for control loops
· Automatic reset on timeout

6.3 Radiation Testing Protocol

NASA GSFC Standards:

1. Total Ionizing Dose: 100 krad(Si) @ 3 rad/s
2. Single Event Effects: Heavy ion testing (LET: 1-86 MeV·cm²/mg)
3. Displacement Damage: Proton testing (50-200 MeV)
4. System-level: Combined environment (radiation + thermal + vacuum)

Qualification Levels:

· Component level: > 100 krad
· Board level: > 50 krad with margin
· System level: > 30 krad with redundancy

